sentences: Carly Pearce (born Carly Cristyne Slusser; April 24, 1990) is an American country music singer and songwriter.
Pearce began performing professionally in her teens, appearing on several albums of bluegrass material in the 2000s.
Pearce first gained major recognition in 2017 when her self-penned "Every Little Thing" found an audience on satellite radio.
Pearce has since released new material, including the 2020 single "Next Girl" from 29, an EP released in February 2021.

2016–present: Breakthrough success ===
In 2016, Pearce was featured on the track "Wasn't That Drunk" by the country group Josh Abbott Band.
Released as a single that year, it peaked at number 37 on the Billboard Country Airplay chart.
The same year, Pearce was being brought to the attention of multiple Nashville record labels.
The same year, busbee produced a track co-written by Pearce entitled "Every Little Thing".
"Every Little Thing" was officially released as a single to country radio in February 2017.
By November, the song had become a major hit, peaking at number five on the Billboard Hot Country Songs chart and number one on the Billboard Country Airplay chart.
Pearce's debut studio album was released the same year, also named Every Little Thing.
In his concluding statement Erlewine commented, "her showbiz and country roots are inextricably entangled, a singer with a feel for the past but an eye for the present."
Jewly Hight of NPR also praised the album, drawing similarities between her vocals and that of artists such as Alison Krauss and Trisha Yearwood.
Her next single release, "Hide the Wine", was spawned from her 2017 album.
It became Pearce's second major hit, reaching number 13 on the Billboard Country Airplay chart in 2018.
The same year, she issued a single that was to be the lead release of her upcoming second studio album.
Entitled "Closer to You", the song was released in November 2018 and reached the top 40 of the Billboard country charts.
In October 2019, Pearce released a second single from her unreleased second studio album.

When reviewing her 2017 studio album, AllMusic's Stephen Thomas Erlewine noted that it "still bears all the hallmarks of contemporary country production.
In Taste of Country's review of Pearce's 2017 album, it was mentioned that several album tracks (such as "Catch Fire") were "pop-leaning" in their sound.

In July 2018, Pearce confirmed that she was dating fellow country singer Michael Ray.
They became engaged on December 19, 2018.
The two were married on October 6, 2019, near Nashville, Tennessee.
In June 2020, Pearce filed for divorce from Ray after eight months of marriage.
